SIMPLE: swagger
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Swagger
<hw>Swag"ger</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Swaggered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Swaggering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Freq. of
<ets>swag</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To walk with a swaying motion;
hence, to walk and act in a pompous, consequential manner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A man who <qex>swaggers</qex> about London clubs.</q>
<rj><qau>Beaconsfield.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To boast or brag noisily; to be ostentatiously proud
or vainglorious; to bluster; to bully.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What a pleasant it is . . . to <qex>swagger</qex> at the bar!</q>
<rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To be great is not . . . to <qex>swagger</qex> at our footmen.</q>
<rj><qau>Colier.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swagger</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Swagger
<hw>Swag"ger</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To bully.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swagger</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Swagger
<hw>Swag"ger</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act or manner of a
swaggerer.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He gave a half <qex>swagger</qex>, half leer, as he stepped forth
to receive us.</q> <rj><qau>W. Irving.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swagger</ent>⟦br⟧

